{{Chess Opening Theory/Position|= |Ruy Lopez:Riga Variation| |rd| |bd| |kd| | |rd|= | |pd|pd| | |pd|pd|pd|= |pd| |nl| | | | | |= | | | |pd| | | | |= |bl| | | |rl| | |qd|= | | | | | | | | |= |pl|pl|pl| | |pl|pl|bd|= |rl|nl|bl|ql| | | |kl|= || }} =Ruy Lopez, Riga Variation, Main Line=
White takes the knight on e4, sacrificing the exchange to remove black's pressure on the f2 square. Now black has two options to retake: with [[/11...Qxe4|11...Qxe4]] or [[/11...dxe4|11...dxe4]].
It turns out that 11...Qxe4, while possibly appealing because it attacks the a4 bishop, is an error. Moving the queen away lessens the pressure on the f2 square and leaves the h2 bishop hanging. White can counter the attack on his bishop with either 12. Nd4 (blocking the attack), or 12. Nc3 (defending the bishop).
Therefore, 11...dxe4 is the main line.
{{ChessMid}} ==References== {{reflist}} {{wikipedia|Ruy Lopez}}
{{Chess Opening Theory/Footer}}

{{Chess Opening Theory/Position|=
|Ruy Lopez:Riga Variation|
   |rd|  |bd|  |kd|  |  |rd|=
