This section is ''limited'' to citable documents. URLs and references of a more general nature should be placed elsewhere.
== Official GLPK documentation ==
The official GLPK documentation is contained within each official GLPK distribution. The key documents are:
{| class="wikitable" ! PDF !! Topic !! Comment |- | <tt>doc/glpk.pdf</tt> | GLPK '''reference manual''' | also covers the C language application programming interface (API)&nbsp; |- | <tt>doc/gmpl.pdf</tt> | GNU '''MathProg modeling language'''&nbsp; | MathProg is sometimes known as GMPL |- | <tt>doc/graphs.pdf</tt>&nbsp; | GLPK '''graph and network routines''' | network programming support |- | <tt>doc/cnfsat.pdf</tt>&nbsp; | '''CNF-SAT problems''' | special case boolean satisfiability problem support |}
The same <tt>doc</tt> directory contains a number of other PDF and text files of a more specialist nature.
These official documents change with each release to reflect developments. These documents are intentionally ''not available'' from this site in order to reduce the maintenance overhead and latency. Note instead the [[GLPK/Obtaining_GLPK|instructions]] for downloading GLPK tarballs.
== Third-party GLPK papers and reports ==
The IBM developerWorks site issued a set of excellent howto's in 2006:
* {{cite web | url=http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/linux/library/l-glpk1/ | title=The GNU Linear Programming Kit, Part 1: Introduction to linear optimization | first=Rodrigo | last=Ceron | date=08 August 2006 | publisher=IBM}}
* {{cite web | url = http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/linux/library/l-glpk2/ | title = The GNU Linear Programming Kit, Part 2: Intermediate problems in linear programming | first = Rodrigo | last = Ceron | date = 07 Sep 2006 | publisher = IBM}}
* {{cite web | url = http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/linux/library/l-glpk3/ | title = The GNU Linear Programming Kit, Part 3: Advanced problems and elegant solutions | first = Rodrigo | last = Ceron | date = 14 Nov 2006 | publisher = IBM}}
And more recently:
* {{cite manual | last = Sottinen | first = Tommi | title = Operations research with GNU Linear Programming Kit | publisher = ORMS1020 course notes. Department of Mathematics and Statistics, University of Vaasa, Finland | date = 2009 | url = http://lipas.uwasa.fi/~tsottine/lecture_notes/or.pdf }} &mdash; Tommi Sottinen’s course notes on operations research and GPLSOL provide an excellent introduction to coding in MathProg.
* {{citation | last1 = Pryor | first1 = Jennifer | last2 = Chinneck | first2 = John W | year = 2011 | title = Faster integer-feasibility in mixed-integer linear programs by branching to force change | periodical = Computers and Operations Research | volume = 38 | issue = 8 | pages = 1143-1152 | doi = 10.1016/j.cor.2010.10.025 }} &mdash; this publication describes changes to GLPK&nbsp;4.28 to test novel MILP branching techniques.
* {{cite web | url = http://proceedings.fedcsis.org/fedcsis2011/223.pdf | last1 = Eleyat | first1 = M. | last2 = Natvig | first2 = L. | last3 = Amundsen | first3 = J. | date= 18-21 Sept. 2011 | title = Cache-aware matrix multiplication on multicore systems for IPM-based LP solvers | publisher = 2011 Federated Conference on Computer Science and Information Systems (FedCSIS), | pages = 431-438 }} &mdash; this publication describes cache aware matrix multiplication algorithms implemented in GLPK&nbsp;4.43.
== Linear programming more generally ==
* {{cite book|last1=Applegate|first1=David L.|last2=Bixby|first2=Robert E.|last3=Cook|first3=William J.|title=The Traveling Salesman Problem: A Computational Study|series=Princeton Series in Applied Mathematics|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2007|isbn=0691129932|ref=App07}}
* {{cite book|last1=Dantzig|first1=George Bernhard|title=Linear Programming and Extensions|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1998|isbn=0691059136|ref=Dan63}} &mdash; A basic text in linear programming and the solution of systems of linear equalities. The subjects covered include the concepts, origins and formulations of linear programs, and the simplex method of solution as applied to the price concept, matrix games, and transportation problems. Also included is sufficient background on convex sets and linear spaces to enable a discussion of topics such as duality, variants of the simplex method, and the extensions of linear programming to convex programs, to programming under uncertainty, and to certain network, topological, and combinatorial problems that may be framed as linear inequalities with integer-valued variables. Parts of an older edition are available online at [http://www.rand.org/pubs/reports/R366 http://www.rand.org/pubs/reports/R366].
* {{cite book|last1=Desaulniers|first1=Guy|last2=Desrosiers|first2=Jacques|last3=Solomon|first3=Marius M.|title=Column Generation|publisher=Springer|year=2005|isbn=1441937994|ref=Des05}}
