The '''McLafferty rearrangement''' is a reaction observed in mass spectrometry. It is sometimes found that a molecule containing a keto-group undergoes β-cleavage, with the gain of the γ-hydrogen atom. This rearrangement may take place by a radical or ionic mechanism.

== The reaction ==
A description of the reaction was first published by the American chemist Fred McLafferty in 1959.<ref>{{cite journal | author = F. W. McLafferty| title = Mass Spectrometric Analysis. Molecular Rearrangements| journal = Anal. Chem. | volume = 31 | issue = 1 | pages = 82–87 | year = 1959 | doi = 10.1021/ac60145a015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Gross ML | title = Focus in honor of Fred McLafferty, 2003 Distinguished Contribution awardee, for the discovery of the "McLafferty Rearrangement" | journal = J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom. | volume = 15 | issue = 7 | pages = 951–5 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15234352 | doi = 10.1016/j.jasms.2004.05.009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Nibbering NM | title = The McLafferty rearrangement: a personal recollection | journal = J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom. | volume = 15 | issue = 7 | pages = 956–8 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15234353 | doi = 10.1016/j.jasms.2004.04.025}}</ref>

[[Image:McLafferty rearrangement.gif|center|500 px|An example of the McLafferty rearrangement]]

