'''Nuclear orientation''', in [[nuclear physics]], is the directional ordering of an assembly of [[nuclear spin]]s with respect to some axis in space.<ref>[http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/nuclear+orientation Nuclear orientation], ''[[The Free Dictionary]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.accessscience.com/abstract.aspx?id=459400 Nuclear orientation], ''[http://www.accessscience.com/ AccessScience]''.</ref>

A [[Nuclear physics|nuclear]] level with [[Spin (physics)|spin]] in a [[magnetic field]] will divide into magnetic sub-levels with an energy spacing.<ref name="nog">[http://www-nog.physics.ox.ac.uk/www/gen/gen.html General Idea of Nuclear Orientation], [http://www-nog.physics.ox.ac.uk/ Nuclear Orientation Group], [[University of Oxford]], UK.</ref>
The populations of these levels are determined by the [[Boltzmann distribution]] at a steady temperature and will essentially be equal. The exponential in the Boltzmann distribution should not be equal to 1 to obtain unequal populations. To achieve this, cooling to a temperature of around 10 milli-Kelvin is needed.
Typically, this is achieved by implanting the [[Atomic nucleus|nuclei]] of interest into [[ferromagnetic]] hosts.

In the mid 1940s, [[Yevgeny Zavoisky]] developed [[electron paramagnetic resonance]], eventually leading to the concept of nuclear orientation.<ref>B. Bleaney and O. V. Lounasmaa, [http://www.jstor.org/stable/3557722 Nuclear Orientation and Nuclear Cooling Experiments in Oxford and Helsinki. Part 2. Progress from 1945 to 1970]. ''[[Notes and Records of the Royal Society of London]]'', Volume 57, Number 3, pages 323–330, September 2003. Published by [[The Royal Society]].</ref>
In the early 1950s, [[Neville Robinson]], [[Jim Daniels (physicist)|Jim Daniels]], and [[Michael Grace (physicist)|Michael Grace]] produced an example of nuclear orientation for the first time at the [[Clarendon Laboratory]], [[University of Oxford]].<ref>Nicholas Kurti, [http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-neville-robinson-1354491.html Obituary: Neville Robinson]. ''[[The Independent]]'', 27 November 1996.</ref>
There is now a Nuclear Orientation Group at Oxford.<ref name="nog" />

